/*

 Trying to parametrize a circle without using trigonometry. Two
 possible ways to do so are:

 * p(t) = sqrt( 1-t, t )
 * p(t) = ( 1-t², 2t ) / (1+t²)

 When plotted you'll see points equidistant in parameter space
 are not equidistant in the plane or across arcelength. The 
 reason is the tangent to the curve, p'(t), has no constant
 length. Let's try to fix it.



 1. Fixing p(t) = sqrt( 1-t, t );

 We compute the length (squared) of the tangent. We wish that
 was a constant, but it's not:

 |p'(t)|² = 1/[ 4·t·(1-t) ]

 We can try to fix it by introducing a reparametrization s(t),
 still to be determined, such that we now do

 p(s(t)) = sqrt( 1-s(t), s(t) )

 and

 |p'(t)|² = s'(t)² / [ 4·s(t)·(1-s(t)) ]

 Since we want the derivative to be constant, we need to
 choose s(t) such that its squared derivative is proportional
 to itself minus its square. That sounds a lot like the kind
 of thing trigonometric functioins do. And indeed, with some
 exploration you can quickly find that

 s(t) = 1/2 - 1/2·cos(PI·t)

 produces exactly a consant derivative! So, 

 s(t) = 1/2 - 1/2·cos(PI·t)
 p(s(t)) = sqrt( 1-s(t), s(t) )

 will produce an perfect circle. However, the point was to
 avoid using trigonometrics. So here's an alternative: do
 s(t) = t²(3-2t), a cubic smoothstep, which is close to the
 cosine curve.

 This approximation only changes the position of the sampling
 points along the circle. The circle itself is still a perfect
 curcle, for |p(t)| is still 1 exactly.



 2. Fixing p(t) = ( 1-t², 2t ) / (1+t²);

 We proceed similary. In this case,

 |p'(t)| = 2/(1+t²)

 So we introduce a reparametrization

 p(s(t)) = p = ( 1-s²(t), 2s(t) ) / (1+s²(t));

 and by the chain rule |p'(s(t))| = |s'(t)|·|p'(s(t))|. Then

 s'(t) = (1+s²(t))·k/2

 Since we want s(0)=0 and s(1)=1, that means k=s'(1)

 s'(t) = (1+s²(t))·s'(1)/2

 which can be fulfilled by s(t) = tan(t*PI/4), so

 s(t) = tan(t*PI/4)
 p(t) = ( 1-t², 2t ) / (1+t²)

 is a perfect cicle. But we can approximate s(t) by  

 s(t) = t*(0.7612+t*t*0.2388) 							 MSE=1.32e-5  ERR=5.4e-3
 s(t) = t*(0.787756+t*t*(0.145251+t*t*0.066993)) 		 MSE=1.06e-7  ERR=4.9e-4
 s(t) = t*(0.7856+t*t*(0.1604+t*t*(0.0382+t*t*0.01578))) MSE=2.35e-9  ERR=8.1e-5

 in which case we still have a perfect circle with
 nearly-perfectly equidistant points. 
*/


// 0 : p(t) = ( cos(t), sin(t) )
// 1 : p(t) = sqrt( 1-t, t )
// 2 : p(t) = ( 1-t², 2t ) / (1+t²)
#define PARMATRIZATION 1

// Make 16 to see more dramatic effets
#define NUMPOINTS 50


//----------------------------------------
const float pi = 3.1415926535;

vec2 circle( in float t )
{
#if PARMATRIZATION==0
    vec2 p = vec2( -sin(2.0*pi*t), cos(2.0*pi*t) );
#endif

#if PARMATRIZATION==1
    float s = fract(t*4.0);

  //s = 0.5-0.5*cos( s*pi ); // exact
    s = s*s*(3.0-2.0*s);       // approximation

    vec2 p = sqrt( vec2(1.0-s,s) );
         if( t<0.25 ) p = vec2(-p.y, p.x);
    else if( t<0.50 ) p = vec2(-p.x,-p.y);
    else if( t<0.75 ) p = vec2( p.y,-p.x);
#endif

#if PARMATRIZATION==2
    float s = fract(t*4.0);

    #if 0
  	s = tan(s*3.14159/4.0);     // exact
    #else 
  	float s2 = s*s; 			// approximation
  //s = s*(0.7612+s2*0.2388);  							// MSE=1.32e-5  ERR=5.4e-3
    s = s*(0.787756+s2*(0.145251+s2*0.066993)); 		// MSE=1.06e-7  ERR=4.9e-4
  //s = s*(0.7856+s2*(0.1604+s2*(0.0382+s2*0.01578))); 	// MSE=2.35e-9  ERR=8.1e-5
    #endif


    vec2 p = vec2( 1.0-s*s, 2.0*s ) / (1.0+s*s);
         if( t<0.25 ) p = vec2(-p.y, p.x);
    else if( t<0.50 ) p = vec2(-p.x,-p.y);
    else if( t<0.75 ) p = vec2( p.y,-p.x);
#endif        

    return p;
}

